ThinkPart(
    type='think',
    think='Now I have enough information to write the review report. Let me summ
arize my findings:\n\n**PR Overview:**\n- PR #30, branch: design/issue-19\n- Red
esigns UI container components (UIPanel, UIDialog, UIToast, UIAlert) to align wi
th PRD-004\n- Also includes UIButton redesign and utils/types updates\n- Updates
docs and adds tests\n- Maintains backward compatibility in apps/phaser3/src/ui/ 
for UIToast (old API wrappers)\n\n**Key Issues Found:**\n\n1. **Blocking - UIBut
ton `setDisabled(false)` doesn\'t re-enable interactive events properly**\n   - 
In `apps/phaser3/src/ui/UIButton.ts` (and `designs/issue-19/src/ui/UIButton.ts`)
, `setDisabled(false)` calls `target.setInteractive({ useHandCursor: true })` bu
t the event handlers were registered in `setupInteraction()` during construction
. If the button was constructed with `isDisabled: true`, the handlers were never
registered (in designs version) OR in the apps version, handlers are always regi
stered but `disableInteractive()` just disables them.\n   - Wait, looking more c
arefully at the apps version: In `setupInteraction()`, it always calls `target.s
etInteractive({ useHandCursor: true })` and registers all event handlers. Then a
t the end, if `isDisabled` is true, it calls `target.disableInteractive()` and `
this.setAlpha(0.6)`.\n   - In `setDisabled(false)`, it calls `target.setInteract
ive({ useHandCursor: true })` and `this.setAlpha(1)`. BUT `disableInteractive()`
was called when disabled. According to Phaser docs, `disableInteractive()` remov
es the input handler. `setInteractive()` re-adds it. But the event listeners (`o
n(\'pointerover\')`, etc.) should still be on the object because `disableInterac
tive()` doesn\'t remove them, it just disables the input plugin handler.\n   - A
ctually, looking at the design spec in `docs/design-docs/ui-style-guide/03-compo
nent.md` line 38: "`setDisabled(false)` 必须恢复完整交互事件监听（事件监听应在构
造时注册，仅在回调内部判断 `isDisabled`；禁止在构造时因 `isDisabled=true` 跳过 `
on(\'pointerover\')` 注册导致后续无法恢复）"\n   - The apps version follows this
pattern correctly! Event listeners are always registered, and `isDisabled` is ch
ecked inside callbacks. `setDisabled(false)` calls `target.setInteractive({ useH
andCursor: true })` which restores interaction. So this is actually CORRECT in a
pps version.\n   - The designs version however sets `useHandCursor: !this.config
.isDisabled` and returns early if disabled, which means events are never registe
red. This violates the spec! But the designs version is the design artifact, and
the apps version is the actual implementation. The PR merged the correct pattern
into apps.\n\n2. **Major - UIDialog test issue: `onConfirm` test doesn\'t actual
ly verify animation completion order**\n   - In `UIDialog.test.ts`, the test "sh
ould call onConfirm after hide animation" emits \'pointerdown\' on the confirm b
utton. But in the mock scene, `MockTweenManager.add()` immediately calls `onComp
lete()` synchronously. So the test passes but doesn\'t really verify the async b
ehavior. However, this is a mock limitation, not a code bug.\n\n3. **Major - UIT
oast backward compatibility breaks `ToastManager.show()` behavior**\n   - In `ap
ps/phaser3/src/ui/UIToast.ts`, the constructor auto-calls `this.show()` (line 11
1: `// backward compatibility: auto-show like old implementation`). But `ToastMa
nager.show()` also doesn\'t explicitly call `toast.show()` because it expects th
e constructor to NOT auto-show (looking at designs/issue-19 version). \n   - Wai
t, let me check: In designs/issue-19 `ToastManager.show()`, it does `toast.show(
)` explicitly. In apps/phaser3 `ToastManager.show()`, it does NOT call `toast.sh
ow()` explicitly because the constructor already auto-shows. This is fine for ba
ckward compatibility but the `UIToast.show()` method now has a guard against `au
toHideEvent`:\n   ```ts\n   show(): void {\n     if (this.autoHideEvent) {\n    
  this.autoHideEvent.remove();\n       this.autoHideEvent = undefined;\n     }\n
    // ...\n   }\n   ```\n   This means if constructor already started the auto-
hide timer and then `ToastManager.show()` calls `toast.show()`, it would remove 
the old timer and restart. But since `ToastManager.show()` doesn\'t call `toast.
show()` in apps version... wait, actually let me re-read:\n   - In apps/phaser3 
`ToastManager.show()`: it creates `new UIToast(...)` and the constructor auto-ca
lls `this.show()`. Then `ToastManager` pushes to array and returns. It does NOT 
call `toast.show()` again. This is correct.\n   - However, `UIToast.static show(
)` in apps version also just does `new UIToast(scene, config)` and returns it, r
elying on constructor auto-show. In designs version, static `show()` explicitly 
calls `toast.show()`. \n   - The designs version constructor does NOT auto-show.
The apps version does. This is an inconsistency but intentional for backward com
patibility.\n\n4. **Major - `UIAlert.show()` uses `UITweens.popup.duration` (200
ms) instead of `UITweens.toastIn.duration` (300ms)**\n   - Wait, PRD-004 section
5.15 says UIAlert animation: "入场：y: +20 → 0，alpha: 0 → 1，duration=200ms，ea
se=\'Back.out\'"\n   - And in 03-component.md (updated docs): "入场：从 `y + 20`
移动到目标位置，`alpha 0 → 1`，`duration=200ms`，`ease=\'Back.out\'`"\n   - So U
IAlert uses 200ms, which is `UITweens.popup.duration`. That\'s correct per spec!
The designs version uses `UITweens.popup.duration` which is 200ms. The apps vers
ion also uses `UITweens.popup.duration`. OK, this is correct.\n\n5. **Major - `U
IAlert.hide()` uses hardcoded `duration: 200` instead of `UITweens.fade.duration
` (150ms)**\n   - PRD-004 5.15 says UIAlert hide: "退场：alpha: 1 → 0，y: 0 → -1
0，duration=200ms，ease=\'Power2\'"\n   - So 200ms is correct per PRD-004! The d
esigns version uses `UITweens.fade.duration` which is 150ms (wrong for UIAlert p
er PRD). The apps version uses hardcoded `200` which is correct for UIAlert.\n  
- But wait, in `docs/design-docs/ui-style-guide/03-component.md`, it says for UI
Alert: "退场：`alpha 1 → 0`，`y - 10`，`duration=200ms`，`ease=\'Power2\'`". So 
200ms is correct.\n   - However, the apps version uses `duration: 200` hardcoded
while `UITweens.fade.duration` is 150ms. This inconsistency is actually correct 
per spec because UIAlert and UIPanel have different hide durations (200ms vs 150
ms). But there\'s no dedicated `UITweens.alertOut` or similar. This is a minor c
ode style issue, not a bug.\n\n6. **Major - `UIButton` in apps/phaser3 doesn\'t 
handle `pressedColor === -1` fallback correctly**\n   - In `UIButton.ts`, `press
edColor: config.pressedColor ?? -1`. The check is `this.config.pressedColor !== 
-1`. But what if user explicitly passes `0` (black) as pressedColor? `0 !== -1` 
is true, so it works. What if user passes `null` or `undefined`? The default is 
`-1`, so it won\'t apply pressed color. This seems acceptable.\n\n7. **Minor - `
designs/issue-19/src/ui/index.ts` exports `UIAlertType` which doesn\'t exist in 
that file**\n   - Looking at `designs/issue-19/src/ui/index.ts` line 44: `export
{ UIAlert, type UIAlertConfig, type UIAlertType } from \'./UIAlert\';`\n   - But
in `designs/issue-19/src/ui/UIAlert.ts`, there is no `UIAlertType` export! The a
pps version has `export type UIAlertType = UINotificationType;` but the designs 
version does not.\n   - This means `designs/issue-19/src/ui/index.ts` has a brok
en export. However, the designs directory is design artifacts. Still, it should 
compile.\n\n8. **Minor - `designs/issue-19/src/ui/index.ts` exports `ToastType` 
which doesn\'t exist in that file**\n   - Looking at `designs/issue-19/src/ui/in
dex.ts` line 45: `export { UIToast, ToastManager, type ToastType, type UIToastCo
nfig } from \'./UIToast\';`\n   - But in `designs/issue-19/src/ui/UIToast.ts`, t
here is no `ToastType` export! The type is `UINotificationType`. The apps versio
n has `export type ToastType = UINotificationType | \'build\' | \'upgrade\' | \'
remove\';`.\n   - So designs/index.ts has broken exports. Again, this is design 
artifacts but should be valid.\n\n9. **Major - `apps/phaser3/src/ui/__tests__/se
tup.ts` doesn\'t match `designs/issue-19/src/ui/__tests__/setup.ts`**\n   - The 
apps version was rewritten to be simpler and doesn\'t export `expectFallbackWarn
` or `assertFallbackWarn` etc. This is fine since it\'s the actual test infrastr
ucture.\n\n10. **Minor - `ProgressToast.ts` still has `export default ProgressTo
ast`**\n    - `docs/design-docs/ui-style-guide/03-component.md` and `PRD-004` bo
th mandate no `export default`. But this is in `city-builder/ui/` which is depre
cated code with a backward compatibility wrapper. The `export default` at line 1
40 violates the spec.\n\n11. **Major - `UIDialog` depth handling issue**\n    - 
In `UIDialog`, the constructor passes `depth: config.depth ?? getNextDepth(UIDep
thLayer.Dialog, scene)` to `UIPanel` super(). Then it also stores `this.dialogCo
nfig.depth` with the same value.\n    - But `UIPanel` constructor calls `this.se
tDepth(this.config.depth)`. So the depth is set correctly.\n    - However, if th
e user passes a custom `depth`, `getNextDepth` is still called in the panelConfi
g for UIPanel, which increments the counter even though the explicit depth is us
ed. This is a minor issue with the depth counter being incremented unnecessarily
when explicit depth is provided.\n\n12. **Blocking - `UIAlert` background doesn\
't use the type color for the background, only the left bar**\n    - The spec sa
ys UIAlert background should be `UITheme.inkBlack` with a 4px left color bar. Th
e implementation does this correctly. In the designs version, `createBackground(
)` had `const color = this.getTypeColor();` which was unused. The apps version r
emoved this unused variable. Good.\n\n13. **Major - `UIToast` in apps version: c
